</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="37.[189,1399,821,1069]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
Although described as a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peters" authorityYear="1878" box="[675,828,821,847]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hildebrandtii">
<emphasis box="[675,828,821,847]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">hildebrandtii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="K. Andersen" authorityYear="1905" box="[848,952,821,847]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="eloquens">
<emphasis box="[848,952,821,847]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">eloquens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was widely accepted to represent a separate species, already beginning with 
<bibRefCitation author="Andersen" box="[669,921,858,885]" firstAuthor="Andersen" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" pagination="648 - 662" refId="ref256356" refString="Andersen K. 1905. A list of the species and subspecies of the genus Rhinolophus, with some notes on their geographical distribution. Annals and Magazine of Natural History ser. 7, 16 (92): 648 - 662. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 03745480509443310" type="journal article" year="1905">Andersen (1905: 660</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Andersen" box="[932,1039,858,884]" firstAuthor="Andersen" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" pagination="1 - 45" refId="ref256410" refString="Andersen K. 1907. Chiropteran notes. Annali del Museo civico di Storia Naturale &quot; Giacomo Doria &quot; ser. 3, 3 (O. S. 43): 1 - 45. Available from https: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 7931441  page / 15 / mode / 1 up [accessed 29 Nov. 2017]." type="journal article" year="1907">1907: 31</bibRefCitation>
, 34), and further 
<bibRefCitation author="Allen" box="[1240,1394,858,884]" firstAuthor="Allen" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" pagination="1 - 763" refId="ref255370" refString="Allen G. M. 1939. A checklist of African mammals. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology 83: 1 - 763. Available from https: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 2781971  page / 7 / mode / 1 up [accessed 29 Nov. 2017]." type="journal article" year="1939">Allen (1939)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Koopman" box="[189,454,894,921]" firstAuthor="Koopman" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" pagination="353 - 444" refId="ref268702" refString="Koopman K. F. 1975. Bats of the Sudan. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 154 (4): 353 - 444. Available from http: // hdl. handle. net / 2246 / 609 [accessed 29 Nov. 2017]." type="journal article" year="1975">Koopman (1975: 389)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Simmons" box="[466,722,894,921]" firstAuthor="Simmons" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" pagination="312 - 567" refId="ref273235" refString="Simmons N. B. 2005. Order Chiroptera. In: Wilson D. E. &amp; Reeder D. M. (eds) Mammal Species of the World: A Taxonomic and Geographic Reference: 312 - 567. The John Hopkins University Press, Baltimore." type="book chapter" year="2005">Simmons (2005: 354)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Cotterill F. P. D." box="[780,1041,894,921]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" pagination="323 - 325" refId="ref258609" refString="Cotterill F. P. D. 2013 a. Rhinolophus eloquens Eloquent Horseshoe Bat. In: Happold M. &amp; Happold D. (eds) Mammals of Africa Volume IV. Hedgehogs, Shrews and Bats: 323 - 325. Bloomsbury Publishing, London." type="book chapter" year="2013">Cotterill (2013a: 323)</bibRefCitation>
. However, some authors, such as 
<bibRefCitation author="Hayman &amp; Hill" box="[222,541,931,958]" firstAuthor="Hayman" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" refId="ref265812" refString="Hayman R. W. &amp; Hill J. E. 1971. Order Chiroptera. In: Meester J. &amp; Setzer H. W. (eds) The Mammals of Africa, an Identification Manual. Part 2. Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington." type="book" year="1971">Hayman &amp; Hill (1971: 22)</bibRefCitation>
, placed 
<taxonomicName authorityName="K. Andersen" authorityYear="1905" box="[639,743,931,957]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="eloquens">
<emphasis box="[639,743,931,957]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">eloquens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ruppell" authorityYear="1842" box="[783,933,932,958]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fumigatus">
<emphasis box="[783,933,932,958]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">R. fumigatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, whereas 
<bibRefCitation author="Kock" box="[1052,1263,931,958]" firstAuthor="Kock" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" pagination="1 - 238" refId="ref268151" refString="Kock D. 1969. Die Fledermaus-Fauna des Sudan (Mammalia, Chiroptera). Abhandlungen der Senckenbergischen naturforschenden Gesellschaft 521: 1 - 238." type="journal article" year="1969">Kock (1969: 121)</bibRefCitation>
considered it a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peters" authorityYear="1868" box="[408,542,968,994]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aethiops">
<emphasis box="[408,542,968,994]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">R. aethiops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(which is currently also considered a synonym of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ruppell" authorityYear="1842" box="[1158,1274,968,994]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fumigatus">
<emphasis box="[1158,1274,968,994]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">fumigatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Cotterill F. P. D." pageId="37" pageNumber="38" pagination="323 - 325" refId="ref258609" refString="Cotterill F. P. D. 2013 a. Rhinolophus eloquens Eloquent Horseshoe Bat. In: Happold M. &amp; Happold D. (eds) Mammals of Africa Volume IV. Hedgehogs, Shrews and Bats: 323 - 325. Bloomsbury Publishing, London." type="book chapter" year="2013">Cotterill (2013a: 324)</bibRefCitation>
indicates that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="K. Andersen" authorityYear="1905" box="[508,612,1005,1031]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="eloquens">
<emphasis box="[508,612,1005,1031]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">eloquens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from either 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ruppell" authorityYear="1842" box="[1003,1119,1005,1031]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fumigatus">
<emphasis box="[1003,1119,1005,1031]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">fumigatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peters" authorityYear="1878" box="[1174,1327,1005,1031]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hildebrandtii">
<emphasis box="[1174,1327,1005,1031]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">hildebrandtii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its size, but the dimensions show a considerable overlap (see key).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="37" pageNumber="38" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="37.[189,1398,1109,1209]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
The map presented by 
<bibRefCitation author="Cotterill F. P. D." box="[456,711,1109,1135]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" pagination="323 - 325" refId="ref258609" refString="Cotterill F. P. D. 2013 a. Rhinolophus eloquens Eloquent Horseshoe Bat. In: Happold M. &amp; Happold D. (eds) Mammals of Africa Volume IV. Hedgehogs, Shrews and Bats: 323 - 325. Bloomsbury Publishing, London." type="book chapter" year="2013">Cotterill (2013a: 324)</bibRefCitation>
shows a very restricted distribution in eastern Africa, with occurrences in 
<collectingCountry box="[366,446,1146,1172]" name="Kenya" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Kenya</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[457,551,1146,1172]" name="Uganda" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Uganda</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[562,714,1146,1172]" name="South Sudan" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">South Sudan</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[725,821,1146,1172]" name="Rwanda" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Rwanda</collectingCountry>
and extreme northeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1131,1195,1146,1172]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">DRC</collectingCountry>
. This agrees very well with the distribution we postulate, although we believe it might also occur in southern 
<collectingCountry box="[1263,1366,1183,1209]" name="Ethiopia" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Ethiopia</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
